1
00:00:11,875 --> 00:00:14,375
[Karasuma] Yakushimae has agreed
to help you again,

2
00:00:15,166 --> 00:00:16,833
to be your guarantor.

3
00:00:19,083 --> 00:00:20,875
We'll arrange a place for you in a shelter

4
00:00:20,958 --> 00:00:23,250
so your location stays confidential,

5
00:00:23,333 --> 00:00:25,083
and we'll help you find work.

6
00:00:25,583 --> 00:00:28,833
So you can cut ties
with Suguru Kanemoto entirely

7
00:00:28,916 --> 00:00:30,333
and then start over again.

8
00:00:31,458 --> 00:00:32,458
[chuckles]

9
00:00:33,875 --> 00:00:34,708
[sighs]

10
00:00:35,416 --> 00:00:37,000
It won't change though.

11
00:00:37,083 --> 00:00:38,041
[poignant music playing]

12
00:00:38,125 --> 00:00:40,375
It doesn't matter where I go.
It'll stay the same.

13
00:00:40,875 --> 00:00:41,708
Uh-huh.

14
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:46,791
I'm always ending up
in the same crap over and over.

15
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:50,125
PIECE OF SHIT

16
00:00:50,208 --> 00:00:51,625
It's just my fate.

17
00:00:53,833 --> 00:00:56,166
I went… to see your father the other day.

18
00:00:56,750 --> 00:00:57,625
Huh?

19
00:00:58,666 --> 00:01:01,958
Sota has been… arrested?

20
00:01:02,541 --> 00:01:04,333
[Karasuma] If he cuts ties with Kanemoto,

21
00:01:04,416 --> 00:01:06,541
there's a chance
that his life will get better.

22
00:01:06,625 --> 00:01:08,375
You can help him do that.

23
00:01:08,458 --> 00:01:15,166
I'm in no position to say anything
to him after everything.

24
00:01:15,250 --> 00:01:16,625
I'm sorry.

25
00:01:19,333 --> 00:01:21,250
Why didn't you ever get
that tattoo removed?

26
00:01:23,041 --> 00:01:26,541
Kanemoto's father,
he was the one who did that to you, right?

27
00:01:27,208 --> 00:01:29,291
Sota has the same tattoo on his arm.

28
00:01:29,875 --> 00:01:32,458
If you get yours removed,
it might change how he feels.

29
00:01:33,083 --> 00:01:35,291
For Sota's sake, let's get it removed.

30
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:42,583
It'd really help Sota out?

31
00:01:43,666 --> 00:01:45,208
Yeah, it would.

32
00:01:48,125 --> 00:01:49,000
Oh.

33
00:01:49,083 --> 00:01:50,583
Then I'll remove it!

34
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:56,458
I'll do anything… to help my son.

35
00:01:57,750 --> 00:01:59,125
He's doing it for me?

36
00:01:59,916 --> 00:02:02,250
Mm-hmm. That's what he said.

37
00:02:03,666 --> 00:02:06,125
[Yakushimae] The doctor doing it
told your dad,

38
00:02:06,833 --> 00:02:09,708
"It hurts a lot.
Are you sure you want to?"

39
00:02:11,291 --> 00:02:13,250
But your dad said he didn't care.

40
00:02:15,666 --> 00:02:17,916
[Karasuma] He said you wound up in prison

41
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,416
because he was
a sorry excuse for a father.

42
00:02:21,291 --> 00:02:24,000
He said he's been blaming himself
all this time.

43
00:02:25,625 --> 00:02:29,625
Mr. Sogabe…
it's time for you to come clean.

44
00:02:43,291 --> 00:02:45,333
Nah, I can't do it. I'm really sorry.

45
00:02:45,416 --> 00:02:48,833
[groans in frustration]
Sogabe, seriously? Why not?

46
00:02:48,916 --> 00:02:52,416
At this point in the conversation,
usually people say "yes," you know?

47
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:54,666
It's stupid to take all the blame
for someone else!

48
00:02:54,750 --> 00:02:57,208
[Sogabe] No.
You two don't understand anything.

49
00:02:59,166 --> 00:03:01,250
Taking the blame is exactly
what I have to do.

50
00:03:01,875 --> 00:03:02,708
Huh?

51
00:03:02,791 --> 00:03:04,125
What do you mean?

52
00:03:05,250 --> 00:03:07,958
Mr. Kujo, he came to visit me yesterday.

53
00:03:08,791 --> 00:03:11,000
[Kujo] The police arrested Mr. Kanemoto
as an accomplice

54
00:03:11,083 --> 00:03:12,583
because of the cocaine

55
00:03:12,666 --> 00:03:15,458
and marijuana they found at your place.

56
00:03:16,916 --> 00:03:17,750
Yeah.

57
00:03:17,833 --> 00:03:21,791
They're trying to get you three years
by charging you with intent to distribute.

58
00:03:22,291 --> 00:03:27,125
But if you insist that it was only
for your personal use, not to sell,

59
00:03:27,208 --> 00:03:29,625
the sentence for that
is only a year and a half.

60
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:36,000
This is another reason

61
00:03:36,541 --> 00:03:39,250
you have to stick to your story
and take the blame.

62
00:03:40,041 --> 00:03:43,416
You can never tell anyone
that Kanemoto was ever involved.

63
00:03:44,875 --> 00:03:46,125
Sure. I get it.

64
00:03:46,625 --> 00:03:48,791
It's okay if things stay the way they are.

65
00:03:50,416 --> 00:03:52,166
[Kujo] No, that's not what I meant.

66
00:03:53,375 --> 00:03:55,666
The law is designed
to protect people's rights.

67
00:03:55,750 --> 00:03:58,958
Thing is,
it cannot protect people's lives.

68
00:03:59,041 --> 00:04:00,083
[melancholy music playing]

69
00:04:00,166 --> 00:04:02,583
If you go and turn on
Mr. Kanemoto like this,

70
00:04:03,083 --> 00:04:04,750
you'll be dead the moment you get out.

71
00:04:06,083 --> 00:04:08,291
If you wanna cut ties with him,

72
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,791
wait until you're out.

73
00:04:11,833 --> 00:04:14,166
Otherwise,
you might not get out of here alive.

74
00:04:15,833 --> 00:04:17,625
[Sogabe] He was protecting me.

75
00:04:18,208 --> 00:04:20,958
Mr. Kujo… making sure I get through this.

76
00:04:31,833 --> 00:04:33,708
[panicked cries]

77
00:04:34,208 --> 00:04:36,208
[theme music playing]

78
00:05:04,333 --> 00:05:05,208
Huh?

79
00:05:09,250 --> 00:05:10,416
Oh, there you are.

80
00:05:12,916 --> 00:05:14,208
Mr. Kujo.

81
00:05:14,291 --> 00:05:15,583
Mr. Karasuma.

82
00:05:17,125 --> 00:05:20,166
I guess I shouldn't be surprised
this stain won't come out.

83
00:05:20,250 --> 00:05:21,083
What?

84
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,333
[sighing] I wanted to eat the takoyaki
from Japan's number one takoyaki,

85
00:05:26,416 --> 00:05:28,166
but they were closed.

86
00:05:28,250 --> 00:05:31,958
So I was eating takoyaki from another
takoyaki place, and I dropped one.

87
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:33,458
Listen, sir.

88
00:05:33,958 --> 00:05:35,625
Sogabe said he's grateful to you,

89
00:05:36,125 --> 00:05:38,000
that you cared about protecting him.

90
00:05:42,666 --> 00:05:44,208
Thank you very much.

91
00:05:45,500 --> 00:05:47,833
I don't judge my clients
based on their social status

92
00:05:47,916 --> 00:05:49,375
or whether they're bad or good.

93
00:05:49,875 --> 00:05:53,750
As an attorney,
I endeavor to be on my client's side.

94
00:05:55,916 --> 00:05:56,750
But

95
00:05:57,750 --> 00:06:00,000
I can only help with their legal issues.

96
00:06:00,083 --> 00:06:01,791
I can't help with the rest of their lives.

97
00:06:02,833 --> 00:06:04,291
Uh, I don't follow you.

98
00:06:05,333 --> 00:06:08,875
Long after the trial is over,
Mr. Sogabe's life will continue.

99
00:06:09,416 --> 00:06:12,625
And there isn't an attorney alive
who can help him with that.

100
00:06:13,541 --> 00:06:16,833
The only ones who can
are those by his side that love him.

101
00:06:59,541 --> 00:07:00,791
Hi, Mom!

102
00:07:02,750 --> 00:07:03,750
[door closing]

103
00:07:06,083 --> 00:07:07,458
Shinji?

104
00:07:07,541 --> 00:07:09,708
Mom, the flowers out there are dried out.

105
00:07:09,791 --> 00:07:11,916
What's up?
You were taking good care of them.

106
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,333
I don't know.
This is a surprise. What brings you by?

107
00:07:14,416 --> 00:07:16,166
I need some summer clothes.

108
00:07:16,250 --> 00:07:17,833
Oh, okay.

109
00:07:18,625 --> 00:07:21,083
Mom, it's so nice outside.

110
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:25,625
You should go out once in a while.

111
00:07:26,166 --> 00:07:28,666
You used to like going
to musicals and concerts.

112
00:07:28,750 --> 00:07:30,166
No, thanks.

113
00:07:30,250 --> 00:07:32,583
I couldn't.
What if someone saw me out having fun?

114
00:07:32,666 --> 00:07:34,125
What… what would people say?

115
00:07:34,208 --> 00:07:36,125
How long are you gonna keep saying that?

116
00:07:36,208 --> 00:07:38,875
Dad's been gone for 18 years.

117
00:07:38,958 --> 00:07:40,916
[melancholy music playing]

118
00:07:43,250 --> 00:07:45,833
Oh, Mom.
I got this for you. The one dad loved.

119
00:07:45,916 --> 00:07:47,208
Eat it later, okay?

120
00:07:54,416 --> 00:07:56,416
DHARMA NAME SHAKU SEIKOKU

121
00:07:59,291 --> 00:08:00,750
[bell dings]

122
00:08:33,583 --> 00:08:37,083
ESSENTIAL GUIDE TO THE SIX CODES
FOR BEGINNERS

123
00:08:40,083 --> 00:08:42,291
THE SIGNIFICANCE OF STUDYING LAW

124
00:08:45,541 --> 00:08:47,000
[music fades]

125
00:08:48,875 --> 00:08:50,416
[Mibu] Thank you, Mr. Kujo.

126
00:08:51,375 --> 00:08:54,375
You did it.
Kanemoto's out after only 20 days.

127
00:08:54,458 --> 00:08:57,000
What's important is that
he wasn't charged.

128
00:08:57,083 --> 00:08:59,750
Time is our most precious resource
after all.

129
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,041
There's no point going to court
if it can be avoided.

130
00:09:06,375 --> 00:09:10,125
[Mibu] <i>This case has made you</i>
<i>a pretty hot topic around here.</i>

131
00:09:11,375 --> 00:09:14,291
Hey, Kujo! I'm really grateful, dude.

132
00:09:14,791 --> 00:09:17,625
I feel the need to express myself
with some freestyle.

133
00:09:17,708 --> 00:09:19,458
Rap! Yeah, let's go!

134
00:09:19,958 --> 00:09:21,166
<i>♪ Kujo's his name ♪</i>

135
00:09:21,250 --> 00:09:22,916
<i>♪ Respect his game ♪</i>

136
00:09:23,500 --> 00:09:26,125
<i>♪ Twenty days in the cage</i>
<i>I was filled with rage ♪</i>

137
00:09:26,208 --> 00:09:28,541
<i>♪ Now I'm free, but you snitched on me ♪</i>

138
00:09:29,125 --> 00:09:33,333
<i>♪ You got me locked in</i>
<i>And now your head's getting smashed in ♪</i>

139
00:09:33,416 --> 00:09:35,458
- [thug laughs]
- [Kanemoto] <i>Yeah!</i>

140
00:09:35,541 --> 00:09:38,375
[Mibu] Would you like to join us
for a yakiniku party

141
00:09:38,458 --> 00:09:40,458
to celebrate Kanemoto's release?

142
00:09:40,541 --> 00:09:41,583
[rapping indistinctly]

143
00:09:41,666 --> 00:09:44,208
I can't tonight. I'm swamped. I'm sorry.

144
00:09:44,291 --> 00:09:46,708
- [men laughing]
- That's okay. I understand.

145
00:09:49,916 --> 00:09:53,458
I'm sure I'll be needing
your services again soon.

146
00:09:53,541 --> 00:09:55,541
[men continue laughing]

147
00:10:01,291 --> 00:10:02,208
[gasps]

148
00:10:02,791 --> 00:10:03,708
Uh.

149
00:10:03,791 --> 00:10:04,833
You…

150
00:10:04,916 --> 00:10:07,875
You want me to take the fall? But…

151
00:10:07,958 --> 00:10:09,958
[mumbling incoherently]

152
00:10:11,291 --> 00:10:13,291
[sobbing]

153
00:10:16,208 --> 00:10:18,208
[Karasuma] <i>So, Kanemoto is out now?</i>

154
00:10:20,416 --> 00:10:21,625
Now that that's over,

155
00:10:21,708 --> 00:10:24,416
let's hope he spends some time
working on his rap skills.

156
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:26,833
He's bound to go after Mr. Sogabe
as soon as he's out.

157
00:10:27,916 --> 00:10:29,166
Most likely.

158
00:10:37,666 --> 00:10:38,916
Going out for a bit.

159
00:10:42,083 --> 00:10:44,708
[door opening, closing]

160
00:10:45,375 --> 00:10:46,291
DAINI OYAMASHO

161
00:10:46,375 --> 00:10:47,875
[Sogabe's dad] I see.

162
00:10:49,166 --> 00:10:50,750
So Kanemoto's son…

163
00:10:50,833 --> 00:10:51,958
[chuckles]

164
00:10:52,041 --> 00:10:53,666
…was released.

165
00:10:55,208 --> 00:10:56,583
I don't think that Sota

166
00:10:57,083 --> 00:10:59,166
will be able to cut ties with him
on his own.

167
00:11:00,125 --> 00:11:02,041
You know, it's not gonna be easy.

168
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,875
He'll need support after he gets out.

169
00:11:05,375 --> 00:11:07,125
From his parents, ideally.

170
00:11:07,208 --> 00:11:08,208
[chuckles]

171
00:11:08,291 --> 00:11:10,041
I understand what you're saying.

172
00:11:10,541 --> 00:11:16,125
I'll ask Sota…
to live here when he… he gets out.

173
00:11:26,291 --> 00:11:27,750
[chuckles]

174
00:11:27,833 --> 00:11:29,250
My wife's ashes.

175
00:11:31,333 --> 00:11:35,833
She left us
when Sota was about to graduate

176
00:11:36,833 --> 00:11:38,083
from elementary.

177
00:11:38,583 --> 00:11:41,125
And she, uh, uh,

178
00:11:41,208 --> 00:11:43,250
never got in touch with us again.

179
00:11:43,958 --> 00:11:44,916
Then about

180
00:11:46,541 --> 00:11:49,416
three years ago,
she came back to me as ashes.

181
00:11:50,333 --> 00:11:51,750
My condolences.

182
00:11:51,833 --> 00:11:52,916
[chuckles]

183
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,333
I don't think Sota remembers her much.

184
00:11:55,875 --> 00:11:57,041
No, he remembers her.

185
00:12:00,166 --> 00:12:03,958
He told me that she had…
come to his school for sports day.

186
00:12:05,375 --> 00:12:06,541
Sports day?

187
00:12:06,625 --> 00:12:09,416
[cheering]

188
00:12:11,666 --> 00:12:14,000
[Sogabe] <i>There she was, with her head down</i>

189
00:12:14,083 --> 00:12:16,375
<i>like it was the end of the world.</i>

190
00:12:16,958 --> 00:12:19,958
I think she was embarrassed
and frustrated because of me.

191
00:12:20,041 --> 00:12:22,208
Sota said she was looking down…

192
00:12:24,375 --> 00:12:26,625
because she was… embarrassed by him.

193
00:12:27,458 --> 00:12:29,250
Uh-uh! No, she wasn't!

194
00:12:29,958 --> 00:12:32,916
That's not… That's not true.

195
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:34,875
[mellow music playing]

196
00:12:34,958 --> 00:12:35,791
COURTHOUSE

197
00:12:35,875 --> 00:12:37,291
[judge] The court's decision.

198
00:12:37,875 --> 00:12:41,291
The defendant is sentenced
to one year and six months in prison.

199
00:12:42,375 --> 00:12:44,416
A humble heart that says, "Yes."

200
00:12:44,500 --> 00:12:47,291
A humble heart that says, "Yes."

201
00:12:47,375 --> 00:12:49,916
A repentant heart that says, "I'm sorry."

202
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:52,458
A repentant heart that says, "I'm sorry."

203
00:12:52,541 --> 00:12:54,833
[officer] A grateful heart
that says, "Thank you."

204
00:12:55,416 --> 00:12:58,166
A grateful heart that says, "Thank you."

205
00:12:58,250 --> 00:13:01,208
[officer] A willing heart that says,
"I will do it for you."

206
00:13:01,291 --> 00:13:04,333
A willing heart that says,
"I will do it for you."

207
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,666
[Sogabe] <i>Prison's full</i>
<i>of all these old guys.</i>

208
00:13:12,875 --> 00:13:15,458
<i>This one's probably around my dad's age.</i>

209
00:13:18,250 --> 00:13:19,166
[guard] Sogabe.

210
00:13:19,791 --> 00:13:20,916
Yes, sir.

211
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:22,375
[guard] You have a visitor.

212
00:13:23,125 --> 00:13:24,166
Yes, sir.

213
00:13:24,250 --> 00:13:25,416
[music fades]

214
00:13:25,500 --> 00:13:26,541
[door opening]

215
00:13:41,083 --> 00:13:42,041
What is it?

216
00:13:43,583 --> 00:13:45,000
I went to see your dad.

217
00:13:45,666 --> 00:13:48,916
He said when you're out,
you should go live with him.

218
00:13:50,458 --> 00:13:51,583
He said that?

219
00:13:51,666 --> 00:13:52,666
[Karasuma] Uh-huh.

220
00:13:53,375 --> 00:13:56,833
And we also… talked about your mom.

221
00:13:57,750 --> 00:13:59,750
When she came to watch you run,

222
00:14:00,250 --> 00:14:02,791
you finished last place,
and you thought she hung her head ashamed,

223
00:14:02,875 --> 00:14:05,750
looking like… the world had ended.

224
00:14:07,708 --> 00:14:08,833
But that wasn't true.

225
00:14:10,500 --> 00:14:13,333
<i>You see, your dad was there that day too.</i>

226
00:14:15,458 --> 00:14:17,125
<i>Your mom was looking down,</i>

227
00:14:17,708 --> 00:14:19,583
<i>not because she was embarrassed,</i>

228
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:23,000
<i>but because you were giving it your all,</i>

229
00:14:24,583 --> 00:14:26,041
<i>which made her cry.</i>

230
00:14:27,666 --> 00:14:29,666
[poignant music playing]

231
00:14:30,750 --> 00:14:31,875
She was…

232
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:34,541
Sota!

233
00:14:37,333 --> 00:14:38,541
Keep running!

234
00:14:41,416 --> 00:14:43,125
Come on, son!

235
00:14:54,750 --> 00:14:56,000
[sighs]

236
00:14:56,083 --> 00:14:57,416
Oh, Mom…

237
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:04,166
We're running an undercover investigation
into Kanemoto

238
00:15:04,250 --> 00:15:06,000
pursuing the drug-dealing angle.

239
00:15:06,625 --> 00:15:10,083
We know you took the fall for Kanemoto
and that he was the one in charge.

240
00:15:10,625 --> 00:15:12,500
You're sticking to your story?

241
00:15:18,166 --> 00:15:20,791
Even if it was just possession,
you're the only one still in here,

242
00:15:20,875 --> 00:15:22,500
and you'll be here for a year and a half.

243
00:15:22,583 --> 00:15:24,250
Does that seem fair to you?

244
00:15:29,333 --> 00:15:32,000
You were using a phone app
to communicate with Kanemoto

245
00:15:32,083 --> 00:15:34,583
about your work
to avoid wiretapping, right?

246
00:15:35,083 --> 00:15:37,833
We're having your phone analyzed
by a specialist.

247
00:15:42,833 --> 00:15:46,375
Well, how do you feel about that, Sogabe?

248
00:15:47,125 --> 00:15:48,791
You have anything to say?

249
00:15:55,250 --> 00:15:57,083
Detective, can I ask you a favor?

250
00:15:59,708 --> 00:16:00,583
What is it?

251
00:16:03,458 --> 00:16:06,000
PIECE OF SHIT

252
00:16:07,083 --> 00:16:08,541
I want this gone.

253
00:16:16,166 --> 00:16:18,416
I want to remove this tattoo.

254
00:16:18,500 --> 00:16:19,666
[music fades]

255
00:16:20,416 --> 00:16:21,916
[dramatic sting]

256
00:16:23,333 --> 00:16:24,333
Yes, sir.

257
00:16:25,041 --> 00:16:30,041
GRAND OPENING!
CONGRATULATIONS!

258
00:16:30,125 --> 00:16:33,333
Yes, Mr. Kyogoku. I understand.

259
00:16:39,875 --> 00:16:41,000
[sighs]

260
00:16:41,083 --> 00:16:42,208
[dramatic music playing]

261
00:16:42,291 --> 00:16:44,291
[vocalizing]

262
00:16:46,208 --> 00:16:47,041
<i>♪ Yo, yo ♪</i>

263
00:16:47,125 --> 00:16:49,125
[continues vocalizing]

264
00:16:50,083 --> 00:16:51,208
Mibu!

265
00:16:51,291 --> 00:16:55,458
Congratulations on the opening
of your club, boss!

266
00:16:55,541 --> 00:16:56,750
[Mibu] Thanks.

267
00:16:56,833 --> 00:16:58,166
Mibu, sir,

268
00:16:58,250 --> 00:17:01,666
business may be going terribly,
but you're doing all right.

269
00:17:01,750 --> 00:17:03,625
Are you sure it's okay
to invite someone like me?

270
00:17:04,208 --> 00:17:05,333
Of course.

271
00:17:07,333 --> 00:17:08,500
Just got the cards in.

272
00:17:08,583 --> 00:17:10,583
[Kanemoto] Thank you very much.

273
00:17:11,625 --> 00:17:14,625
Mibu's Gentleman's Club!

274
00:17:14,708 --> 00:17:17,208
[kisses]

275
00:17:17,291 --> 00:17:19,083
You're coming too, right?

276
00:17:19,750 --> 00:17:21,875
I have to finish
and deliver a car by tomorrow.

277
00:17:21,958 --> 00:17:22,875
Oh!

278
00:17:23,958 --> 00:17:25,625
Do you mind closing the main door?

279
00:17:26,666 --> 00:17:27,833
It's the orange button.

280
00:17:27,916 --> 00:17:29,041
Oh, okay.

281
00:17:29,875 --> 00:17:32,625
[vocalizing]

282
00:17:33,416 --> 00:17:35,958
[Kanemoto]
You're such a hard worker, Mibu.

283
00:17:37,250 --> 00:17:40,333
Is this river water over here? How come?

284
00:17:40,416 --> 00:17:42,791
Yeah. It saves money.

285
00:17:42,875 --> 00:17:44,000
[Kanemoto] <i>♪ Yo, yo ♪</i>

286
00:17:44,083 --> 00:17:45,041
[vocalizing]

287
00:17:45,125 --> 00:17:46,250
<i>♪ In the club ♪</i>

288
00:17:47,666 --> 00:17:51,250
Miyoko, I'm sorry. I love you.

289
00:17:51,333 --> 00:17:53,458
[vocalizing]

290
00:17:53,541 --> 00:17:55,125
- [stun gun zapping]
- [Kanemoto grunts]

291
00:18:05,250 --> 00:18:07,250
[tense music playing]

292
00:18:33,250 --> 00:18:35,250
[hose blasting]

293
00:18:45,375 --> 00:18:46,291
Mibu?

294
00:18:48,041 --> 00:18:48,916
Mibu!

295
00:18:50,416 --> 00:18:51,291
Mibu!

296
00:18:52,041 --> 00:18:52,916
Mibu!

297
00:18:56,291 --> 00:18:57,375
Mibu!

298
00:18:57,875 --> 00:18:58,750
Mibu!

299
00:18:59,333 --> 00:19:00,333
Mibu!

300
00:19:02,083 --> 00:19:03,333
Mibu!

301
00:19:03,416 --> 00:19:04,500
[music fades]

302
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:10,291
You know the criminal organization
Kanemoto and his men were working for,

303
00:19:10,375 --> 00:19:11,375
the Fushimi-gumi?

304
00:19:11,458 --> 00:19:13,833
One of its executives was busted
for smuggling cocaine.

305
00:19:13,916 --> 00:19:16,166
You're not saying
Kanemoto snitched on them?

306
00:19:16,666 --> 00:19:17,875
No.

307
00:19:17,958 --> 00:19:21,083
Kanemoto owed the Fushimi-gumi
everything he had.

308
00:19:21,166 --> 00:19:23,500
No, someone else was the snitch.

309
00:19:23,583 --> 00:19:24,458
Who was it?

310
00:19:27,416 --> 00:19:28,708
Sogabe did it.

311
00:19:29,500 --> 00:19:30,791
Sogabe?

312
00:19:31,875 --> 00:19:36,208
He took a shot at them from inside prison
while he was at least a bit safer.

313
00:19:36,708 --> 00:19:38,375
Sogabe understands how things work, so

314
00:19:39,083 --> 00:19:42,625
he framed Kanemoto as the snitch,
and it looks like they bought it.

315
00:19:44,083 --> 00:19:46,750
And apparently he told the detective,

316
00:19:48,250 --> 00:19:52,208
"I want to remove my tattoo
just like my father."

317
00:19:54,958 --> 00:19:58,541
I guess he must've finally found
the resolve to break the vicious cycle.

318
00:20:03,708 --> 00:20:05,166
Mr. Karasuma.

319
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:08,416
You managed to do it after all.

320
00:20:08,916 --> 00:20:09,791
You saved him.

321
00:20:17,708 --> 00:20:19,416
What's with that look on your face?

322
00:20:20,958 --> 00:20:22,208
I feel good, but…

323
00:20:23,833 --> 00:20:27,458
I don't know if that's right.
Not sure what I should be feeling.

324
00:20:28,833 --> 00:20:30,083
I hear you.

325
00:20:31,791 --> 00:20:35,416
Is this what it's like for you too,
Mr. Kujo?

326
00:20:37,375 --> 00:20:40,041
[Kujo] I… don't really think about it.

327
00:20:41,291 --> 00:20:42,291
[Karasuma] I see.

328
00:20:46,416 --> 00:20:50,500
Anyway, the most important thing
for Mr. Sogabe is whatever happens next.

329
00:20:51,750 --> 00:20:52,666
Happens next?

330
00:20:53,166 --> 00:20:55,083
Well, depending on what Kanemoto does.

331
00:20:56,041 --> 00:20:57,000
[sighs]

332
00:20:59,416 --> 00:21:02,375
Actually,
he was found floating in the river.

333
00:21:02,458 --> 00:21:03,666
What?

334
00:21:05,791 --> 00:21:07,791
[melancholy music playing]

335
00:21:12,166 --> 00:21:14,958
[Kujo] <i>Drowning was confirmed</i>
<i>as cause of death.</i>

336
00:21:15,041 --> 00:21:19,583
<i>The water in his lungs was river water,</i>
<i>the same river water he was found in.</i>

337
00:21:21,625 --> 00:21:24,583
So, Kanemoto was killed
because they thought he was a snitch?

338
00:21:55,166 --> 00:21:56,625
[music fades]

339
00:21:58,500 --> 00:21:59,708
[door opens]

340
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:02,291
- [Karasuma] Come in.
- [Sogabe's dad] Thank you.

341
00:22:03,125 --> 00:22:05,583
Mr. Kujo, it's Mr. Sogabe's father.

342
00:22:06,166 --> 00:22:07,083
[Kujo] Ah.

343
00:22:08,208 --> 00:22:09,250
Pleasure to meet you.

344
00:22:09,333 --> 00:22:14,416
Thanks, sir.
I'm so grateful to you… for saving my son.

345
00:22:16,083 --> 00:22:18,458
Looks good.
Your forehead's looking much better.

346
00:22:18,541 --> 00:22:20,916
Oh, yeah! Oh, yeah. [chuckles]

347
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:24,958
Oh, thank you for letting me pay
the attorney's fees

348
00:22:25,041 --> 00:22:26,250
over time with no interest.

349
00:22:26,333 --> 00:22:27,500
It's a great help, sir.

350
00:22:27,583 --> 00:22:29,333
No worries. Thanks for making the trip.

351
00:22:29,416 --> 00:22:30,666
[Sogabe's dad] No, thank you.

352
00:22:30,750 --> 00:22:34,708
Oh! Please! I brought you some treats.

353
00:22:34,791 --> 00:22:35,666
[all exclaiming]

354
00:22:35,750 --> 00:22:38,041
Oh, thank you very much.
That's very kind of you.

355
00:22:38,125 --> 00:22:40,041
[upbeat music playing]

356
00:22:40,125 --> 00:22:41,000
Oden?

357
00:22:41,083 --> 00:22:42,208
In the summer?

358
00:22:42,291 --> 00:22:45,583
I went to four convenience stores
and bought only eggs.

359
00:22:45,666 --> 00:22:47,916
I was finally able to get 25!

360
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:50,291
- [Karasuma chuckles]
- That's some kind of shopping.

361
00:22:50,375 --> 00:22:53,625
- Eggs are mine and Sota's favorite.
- Ah.

362
00:22:53,708 --> 00:22:56,000
Here's hoping you like them too.

363
00:22:56,083 --> 00:22:57,000
[chuckles]

364
00:22:57,583 --> 00:22:58,458
Uh…

365
00:22:59,083 --> 00:23:01,166
I'm a daikon man, actually.

366
00:23:01,250 --> 00:23:02,166
[music stops abruptly]

367
00:23:02,250 --> 00:23:03,125
What?

368
00:23:03,208 --> 00:23:04,958
Was that really necessary?

369
00:23:06,708 --> 00:23:08,000
Well, then, Yakushimae…

370
00:23:08,083 --> 00:23:09,875
I'm a chikuwa girl.

371
00:23:09,958 --> 00:23:10,916
Ah.

372
00:23:11,708 --> 00:23:12,958
- All the more for me then.
- Oh!

373
00:23:13,041 --> 00:23:13,958
[Sogabe's dad chuckles]

374
00:23:14,041 --> 00:23:14,958
Go ahead.

375
00:23:15,041 --> 00:23:17,000
Thank you for the food.

376
00:23:17,625 --> 00:23:18,750
Looks good.

377
00:23:21,666 --> 00:23:23,458
- Mmm! Mmm!
- [Sogabe's dad laughs]

378
00:23:23,541 --> 00:23:24,750
[Yakushimae] Oh!

379
00:23:24,833 --> 00:23:26,000
[music fades]

380
00:23:26,083 --> 00:23:27,208
By the way,

381
00:23:28,541 --> 00:23:30,083
the other day,

382
00:23:30,875 --> 00:23:33,250
I found Kanemoto's father
drunk outside my house.

383
00:23:42,291 --> 00:23:43,666
[Kanemoto's father sighs]

384
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:51,291
Sogabe.

385
00:23:53,041 --> 00:23:55,583
I apologize to you for everything.

386
00:23:56,875 --> 00:23:58,375
Please forgive me.

387
00:23:58,875 --> 00:24:03,458
I have done… so many horrible

388
00:24:04,458 --> 00:24:06,875
things to you and your son.

389
00:24:09,208 --> 00:24:11,333
I regret it every day.

390
00:24:11,958 --> 00:24:13,833
It's too late for that!

391
00:24:13,916 --> 00:24:16,833
I will never forgive you!

392
00:24:17,708 --> 00:24:19,625
Go away!

393
00:24:20,125 --> 00:24:22,125
[melancholy music playing]

394
00:24:22,208 --> 00:24:24,208
[choir vocalizing]

395
00:24:37,833 --> 00:24:41,666
[Sogabe's dad] <i>Kanemoto, who used</i>
<i>to swagger around so full of himself…</i>

396
00:24:42,958 --> 00:24:45,166
<i>He looked so small and deflated.</i>

397
00:24:46,166 --> 00:24:48,500
I don't care about everything
he did to me.

398
00:24:49,833 --> 00:24:51,750
But I can't forgive him
for what he did to Sota!

399
00:24:51,833 --> 00:24:53,000
[choked sob]

400
00:24:53,500 --> 00:24:56,291
I'm sure he's grieving
the loss of his son right now.

401
00:24:57,333 --> 00:25:01,208
No matter what kind of person he was,
he was still his child.

402
00:25:04,666 --> 00:25:06,666
Were you able to go visit Sota?

403
00:25:06,750 --> 00:25:09,166
Oh, yeah, yeah!
Um, I finally got to see him.

404
00:25:09,250 --> 00:25:11,250
- [Karasuma] Was he happy to see you?
- [laughs]

405
00:25:11,333 --> 00:25:12,583
We, uh…

406
00:25:12,666 --> 00:25:15,541
We didn't know how to act
around each other…

407
00:25:15,625 --> 00:25:16,458
[chuckles]

408
00:25:16,541 --> 00:25:18,666
…so we were quiet at first, you know.

409
00:25:21,083 --> 00:25:22,125
But then

410
00:25:22,708 --> 00:25:24,875
we talked about living together

411
00:25:25,416 --> 00:25:28,750
when he finishes his sentence
and gets out.

412
00:25:28,833 --> 00:25:30,583
Oh, that's great!

413
00:25:30,666 --> 00:25:31,750
[exclaims]

414
00:25:32,666 --> 00:25:35,833
Please accept my eternal gratitude!

415
00:25:36,875 --> 00:25:38,000
[music fades]

416
00:25:40,250 --> 00:25:41,375
[grunts]

417
00:25:42,916 --> 00:25:44,916
[indistinct chatter]

418
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:47,000
[pop music playing over radio]

419
00:25:50,833 --> 00:25:53,041
What the hell is wrong with you?
You're not hungry?

420
00:25:53,666 --> 00:25:55,250
Oh yeah, I just…

421
00:25:55,791 --> 00:25:57,041
[chuckles] Rookie.

422
00:25:57,791 --> 00:26:00,750
He just witnessed the autopsy
of Kanemoto's body.

423
00:26:01,250 --> 00:26:04,000
[gulps] The pig's feet remind me of…

424
00:26:04,083 --> 00:26:05,500
- [man chuckles]
- [gags]

425
00:26:05,583 --> 00:26:06,916
That happened to me too.

426
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:11,458
A guy killed, uh, three workers
at a Chinese restaurant

427
00:26:11,541 --> 00:26:14,333
with a chef's knife,
and the place was a sea of blood.

428
00:26:15,458 --> 00:26:18,958
There were insides scattered everywhere,
and the smell…

429
00:26:19,041 --> 00:26:21,125
I couldn't eat organ meat for a week.

430
00:26:21,208 --> 00:26:22,375
[chuckles]

431
00:26:23,666 --> 00:26:26,833
But once you get used to it,
it doesn't bother you at all.

432
00:26:28,833 --> 00:26:30,541
So, Arashiyama,

433
00:26:31,208 --> 00:26:33,916
Kanemoto's killer,
he was a Yakuza, is that right?

434
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:35,708
- Nah.
- [gags]

435
00:26:35,791 --> 00:26:37,291
It doesn't look like it.

436
00:26:38,125 --> 00:26:40,791
But a guy called Mibu smells fishy.

437
00:26:40,875 --> 00:26:42,416
[upbeat music playing]

438
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:45,625
[Arashiyama] <i>He had a lot of run-ins</i>
<i>with the police as a kid.</i>

439
00:26:46,875 --> 00:26:49,166
<i>But recently, he's wised up.</i>

440
00:26:50,041 --> 00:26:53,333
<i>Officially,</i>
<i>he just owns his own auto-repair shop.</i>

441
00:26:55,291 --> 00:26:58,666
<i>But behind the scenes,</i>
<i>Mibu's connected to the Fushimi-gumi.</i>

442
00:26:59,166 --> 00:27:01,833
<i>He's involved in running</i>
<i>their nightclub operations.</i>

443
00:27:02,333 --> 00:27:04,000
I've heard that too.

444
00:27:04,083 --> 00:27:06,291
He does favors for the gangs,

445
00:27:06,375 --> 00:27:09,125
and he takes what they pay him
and invests it to expand his influence.

446
00:27:09,208 --> 00:27:12,583
We grilled him about the Kanemoto case,
but we had nothing on him.

447
00:27:13,541 --> 00:27:19,125
Also… there's a lawyer close to him,
who's starting to get interesting.

448
00:27:19,208 --> 00:27:20,458
A lawyer, sir?

449
00:27:20,541 --> 00:27:21,541
[Arashiyama] Yeah.

450
00:27:22,125 --> 00:27:24,500
I'm telling you, a lawyer
who hangs out with guys like that?

451
00:27:24,583 --> 00:27:26,500
He'll screw up
and be disbarred soon enough.

452
00:27:26,583 --> 00:27:27,541
[Arashiyama] No.

453
00:27:27,625 --> 00:27:29,541
Kujo is what he's called.

454
00:27:30,083 --> 00:27:32,458
And he's really good at what he does.

455
00:27:34,333 --> 00:27:37,416
We'll face that guy sooner or later.

456
00:27:42,291 --> 00:27:43,875
[music fades]

457
00:27:43,958 --> 00:27:47,291
Come. Come here. Come here.
Hey, hey. Want a treat? Come here.

458
00:27:47,375 --> 00:27:49,250
I think she's afraid of you, Yakushimae.

459
00:27:49,333 --> 00:27:50,750
[Yakushimae] Huh? Why?

460
00:27:50,833 --> 00:27:52,625
Why would she be afraid of me?

461
00:27:52,708 --> 00:27:54,208
Come on. I'm not scary. Come here.

462
00:27:54,291 --> 00:27:56,416
- You can try giving this to her.
- Come here.

463
00:27:56,500 --> 00:27:57,625
To Black Thunder.

464
00:27:57,708 --> 00:27:58,708
Black Thunder?

465
00:27:58,791 --> 00:27:59,625
[Yakushimae] Huh?

466
00:27:59,708 --> 00:28:01,500
That's what they named her.

467
00:28:01,583 --> 00:28:02,583
[Karasuma] Hmm. Hmm.

468
00:28:02,666 --> 00:28:04,166
[Yakushimae] You want this? Oh!

469
00:28:05,625 --> 00:28:08,708
Are you sure
you're going to keep Kanemoto's dog?

470
00:28:08,791 --> 00:28:11,250
Why on earth would you want to, Mr. Kujo?

471
00:28:11,333 --> 00:28:13,791
I wanted to leave the dog
with Kanemoto's girlfriend,

472
00:28:13,875 --> 00:28:15,916
but she said she'd have her put down.

473
00:28:16,500 --> 00:28:18,125
Mibu didn't want her either,

474
00:28:18,208 --> 00:28:21,791
because he said he hasn't gotten over
the death of his own dog, Omochi.

475
00:28:22,500 --> 00:28:24,125
So I didn't have a choice.

476
00:28:25,125 --> 00:28:26,666
Omochi and Black Thunder…

477
00:28:26,750 --> 00:28:29,833
What happened to the classic names
like Buddy, Buster, or Rex?

478
00:28:30,333 --> 00:28:31,250
Beats me.

479
00:28:32,416 --> 00:28:34,750
Well, I'm heading out. See you later.

480
00:28:34,833 --> 00:28:35,750
You're going jogging?

481
00:28:37,625 --> 00:28:38,500
No.

482
00:28:39,875 --> 00:28:42,041
Today is actually my daughter's birthday.

483
00:28:42,125 --> 00:28:43,583
- Oh, how old…
- What?

484
00:28:43,666 --> 00:28:44,833
…is Rino again?

485
00:28:44,916 --> 00:28:46,458
She's five.

486
00:28:46,541 --> 00:28:47,541
[Yakushimae] Already, huh?

487
00:28:47,625 --> 00:28:49,416
So, are you going out
with her to celebrate?

488
00:28:49,500 --> 00:28:50,625
[sighs]

489
00:28:50,708 --> 00:28:52,875
I'm not allowed to see her.

490
00:28:52,958 --> 00:28:55,791
So, I… mailed her a present instead.

491
00:28:57,208 --> 00:28:58,958
[Karasuma] Then where are you going?

492
00:29:12,500 --> 00:29:15,375
[family] One, two, three, jump!

493
00:29:16,291 --> 00:29:17,625
[mother] Ready…

494
00:29:17,708 --> 00:29:20,333
[family] One, two, three, jump!

495
00:29:21,458 --> 00:29:23,708
<i>Daddy, thank you for the present.</i>

496
00:29:23,791 --> 00:29:25,541
[poignant music playing]

497
00:29:28,416 --> 00:29:29,875
[Yakushimae] Poor Kujo.

498
00:29:30,625 --> 00:29:33,375
He gave his ex-wife everything
in the divorce,

499
00:29:33,458 --> 00:29:36,625
and he's paying child support,
but he still can't see his daughter.

500
00:29:38,500 --> 00:29:41,333
[Karasuma] Oh. I guess that's why
he's living in a tent.

501
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:43,333
Yup, bingo.

502
00:29:45,291 --> 00:29:48,500
Why didn't he petition the court
to allow supervised visits?

503
00:29:49,041 --> 00:29:53,000
Well, I'm sure
that Mr. Kujo has his own reasons,

504
00:29:53,083 --> 00:29:54,333
whatever they are.

505
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:55,916
[Karasuma] Hmm…

506
00:29:57,958 --> 00:30:00,250
If he didn't go see his daughter,
where did he go?

507
00:30:01,250 --> 00:30:02,958
Hmm, probably

508
00:30:03,041 --> 00:30:04,416
to see his father.

509
00:30:04,500 --> 00:30:06,000
Hmm? Mr. Kujo's?

510
00:30:06,500 --> 00:30:08,125
Prosecutor Kurama, right?

511
00:30:08,791 --> 00:30:09,916
Mm-hmm.

512
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,250
Didn't he pass away a long time ago?

513
00:30:12,750 --> 00:30:13,833
Mmm.

514
00:30:14,750 --> 00:30:15,875
That's right.

515
00:30:23,291 --> 00:30:24,250
THE KURAMA FAMILY GRAVE

516
00:30:24,333 --> 00:30:26,166
[Yakushimae] <i>His daughter's birthday</i>

517
00:30:26,250 --> 00:30:30,958
<i>and the anniversary of his father's death</i>
<i>are both on August 15th.</i>

518
00:30:31,041 --> 00:30:31,916
Oh.

519
00:30:33,708 --> 00:30:34,625
Okay.

520
00:30:35,500 --> 00:30:36,750
I'll head home.

521
00:30:38,541 --> 00:30:39,500
Hey, Yakushimae.

522
00:30:39,583 --> 00:30:40,583
Huh?

523
00:30:40,666 --> 00:30:43,791
Do you know why
Mr. Kujo uses his ex-wife's last name?

524
00:30:44,375 --> 00:30:46,458
Why don't you ask him that yourself?

525
00:31:06,750 --> 00:31:07,958
What are you doing?

526
00:31:12,333 --> 00:31:17,041
What are you doing at the grave
of the family who disowned you?

527
00:31:19,250 --> 00:31:20,958
I'm praying to Mother.

528
00:31:21,458 --> 00:31:23,166
Father too, just in case.

529
00:31:24,208 --> 00:31:27,083
You are no longer a member
of the Kurama family.

530
00:31:28,083 --> 00:31:29,375
You're no longer my brother.

531
00:31:30,916 --> 00:31:32,625
Save your breath. I was just leaving.

532
00:31:32,708 --> 00:31:34,458
Take those flowers with you.

533
00:31:35,750 --> 00:31:37,416
They defile the grave.

534
00:31:37,500 --> 00:31:39,458
[upbeat music playing]

535
00:31:42,458 --> 00:31:46,291
You're just like the old man,
condescending and arrogant.

536
00:31:46,375 --> 00:31:48,708
I understand you found
the trial upsetting.

537
00:31:48,791 --> 00:31:50,416
Do you have something to say?

538
00:31:54,083 --> 00:31:55,416
Tell him the truth.

539
00:31:55,500 --> 00:31:58,041
If you have a problem with me,
tell me to my face.

540
00:32:00,083 --> 00:32:02,250
I… I think it was obvious.

541
00:32:03,375 --> 00:32:05,083
That defendant was insane.

542
00:32:05,625 --> 00:32:08,291
I don't think it was right
to seek the death penalty.

543
00:32:08,375 --> 00:32:12,333
A crazy murderer like that
deserves the death penalty.

544
00:32:12,416 --> 00:32:15,833
It's our duty as prosecutors
to seek justice on behalf of victims

545
00:32:15,916 --> 00:32:17,500
to ensure faith in the system.

546
00:32:17,583 --> 00:32:19,625
Not at the expense of rational thought.

547
00:32:20,291 --> 00:32:25,166
Even if he was under the influence
of hallucinations and delusions,

548
00:32:25,250 --> 00:32:28,875
the defense failed to prove that
those were the only motivating factors

549
00:32:28,958 --> 00:32:29,875
that made him a killer.

550
00:32:31,125 --> 00:32:34,458
That's why the court chose
the death penalty.

551
00:32:34,958 --> 00:32:36,125
Tell me I'm wrong.

552
00:32:41,208 --> 00:32:42,291
Taiza!

553
00:32:42,791 --> 00:32:45,875
Are you sure
that you want to be a prosecutor?

554
00:32:49,208 --> 00:32:51,000
Wasn't it your mother's last wish?

555
00:32:51,666 --> 00:32:53,500
Didn't you promise to honor that wish?

556
00:32:56,041 --> 00:32:58,625
[Kujo's brother] <i>It's because you have</i>
<i>no discipline, Taiza.</i>

557
00:32:58,708 --> 00:33:00,916
How many times did it take you
to pass the bar?

558
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,041
I can't imagine how a brainless sloth
like you got your own office.

559
00:33:05,166 --> 00:33:09,000
Actually, I can imagine.
I guess crime does pay, huh?

560
00:33:10,125 --> 00:33:13,666
Even among prosecutors,
you're getting quite a reputation.

561
00:33:18,333 --> 00:33:22,125
You're a disgrace to the name Kurama.

562
00:33:26,541 --> 00:33:30,375
There's something I can see
that you've never been able to see.

563
00:33:32,291 --> 00:33:33,541
And what is that?

564
00:33:38,458 --> 00:33:41,208
You're running away
because you know you can't win.

565
00:33:43,041 --> 00:33:45,916
You're a loser who always runs away.

566
00:33:55,041 --> 00:33:57,041
[cell phone vibrating]

567
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:03,250
ATTORNEY YUZO YAMASHIRO

568
00:34:05,708 --> 00:34:07,958
Hello. This is Kujo.

569
00:34:08,041 --> 00:34:08,958
[chuckles]

570
00:34:09,041 --> 00:34:10,500
Oh my goodness.

571
00:34:10,583 --> 00:34:11,666
[chuckles]

572
00:34:11,750 --> 00:34:13,708
Allow me. You're amazing.

573
00:34:13,791 --> 00:34:15,375
- Let me…
- [sighs]

574
00:34:15,458 --> 00:34:16,666
…get you another.

575
00:34:16,750 --> 00:34:19,708
- [chuckles]
- Oh my goodness, sir. That is not allowed.

576
00:34:19,791 --> 00:34:21,708
- Come on. Just for a second.
- Oh, no…

577
00:34:21,791 --> 00:34:23,583
Right, President Sugawara?

578
00:34:24,208 --> 00:34:26,125
- [laughs]
- Behave.

579
00:34:26,208 --> 00:34:29,416
Mr. Yamashiro?
Pardon me, sir. Your guest has arrived.

580
00:34:29,500 --> 00:34:30,708
[Yamashiro] Oh, you're here.

581
00:34:30,791 --> 00:34:32,750
Mr. Yamashiro. It's been too long.

582
00:34:33,333 --> 00:34:37,166
Mr. Kujo, uh, what's that you're wearing?
Is that a sweatsuit?

583
00:34:37,250 --> 00:34:39,833
I was out jogging when you called me.

584
00:34:41,041 --> 00:34:43,458
I'm surprised this place
is open during the day.

585
00:34:43,541 --> 00:34:46,208
Well, that's because
I'm a very good customer.

586
00:34:46,291 --> 00:34:47,125
[hostess chuckles]

587
00:34:47,208 --> 00:34:50,208
So, today is the anniversary
of your father's death?

588
00:34:50,291 --> 00:34:51,375
Yes.

589
00:34:51,458 --> 00:34:53,583
[Yamashiro] Well,
I wanted to introduce you to someone,

590
00:34:53,666 --> 00:34:55,750
partly to pay respects to your father.

591
00:34:55,833 --> 00:34:58,166
This is President Sugawara.

592
00:34:59,458 --> 00:35:01,625
Call me Sugawara.

593
00:35:02,416 --> 00:35:04,083
Nice to meet you. I'm Mr. Kujo.

594
00:35:04,166 --> 00:35:05,958
[Yamashiro grunts] President.

595
00:35:06,541 --> 00:35:08,708
I shouldn't be saying this
considering I'm like his

596
00:35:08,791 --> 00:35:10,125
second father, but, uh,

597
00:35:10,208 --> 00:35:13,583
this is the best attorney
that ever worked for me right here.

598
00:35:13,666 --> 00:35:14,625
[chuckles]

599
00:35:14,708 --> 00:35:16,708
He's like a son to me. You can trust him.

600
00:35:16,791 --> 00:35:17,666
[chuckles]

601
00:35:17,750 --> 00:35:20,000
- You flatter me, sir. Thank you.
- [Yamashiro laughs]

602
00:35:20,083 --> 00:35:22,291
Come on. Sit, sit, sit. Have a drink.

603
00:35:22,875 --> 00:35:24,791
Uh, what's the most expensive
drink you have?

604
00:35:24,875 --> 00:35:26,458
Oh, I'll just have a highball, thank you.

605
00:35:26,541 --> 00:35:29,375
- Yes, sir.
- He's always so stingy, aren't you?

606
00:35:30,083 --> 00:35:33,041
You gotta get the right clients
and make tons of money.

607
00:35:33,125 --> 00:35:35,333
- [tense music playing]
- It's a different world.

608
00:35:35,416 --> 00:35:38,291
Criminal defense is all right
if you know the tricks.

609
00:35:38,375 --> 00:35:40,083
Is that right, sir?

610
00:35:40,583 --> 00:35:41,583
That's right.

611
00:35:41,666 --> 00:35:44,625
Today, I'm giving you
the complete lesson on making money.

612
00:35:44,708 --> 00:35:46,500
- All right?
- [hostess laughs]

613
00:35:46,583 --> 00:35:48,458
[Yamashiro] All right! Gimme another!

614
00:35:48,541 --> 00:35:51,041
<i>You know, that Mr. Sugawara,</i>

615
00:35:51,125 --> 00:35:53,458
he says he runs a nursing home,

616
00:35:54,208 --> 00:35:56,833
but what he really does
is fraud and robbery.

617
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:01,250
And it's guys like him
who have the money these days.

618
00:36:02,875 --> 00:36:06,958
Well… he's better than
the stingy bottom feeders.

619
00:36:08,791 --> 00:36:12,125
That scum is a menace to society.

620
00:36:14,166 --> 00:36:18,000
They should all rot in prison.
Get them off the streets.

621
00:36:20,458 --> 00:36:22,708
[Kujo] You're not on their side anymore?

622
00:36:24,291 --> 00:36:25,208
Huh?

623
00:36:25,291 --> 00:36:26,875
[Kujo] I learned it from you, sir,

624
00:36:27,958 --> 00:36:29,250
that as defense attorneys,

625
00:36:29,333 --> 00:36:31,125
we must always be
on the side of our clients.

626
00:36:35,500 --> 00:36:36,625
[Yamashiro grunts]

627
00:36:38,583 --> 00:36:39,583
Kujo,

628
00:36:41,583 --> 00:36:43,750
I'm not sure what an attorney is.

629
00:36:48,583 --> 00:36:50,208
You're not sure either, are you?

630
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:53,166
[sighs]

631
00:36:54,208 --> 00:36:55,708
Mr. Kujo,

632
00:36:56,291 --> 00:36:57,375
I…

633
00:36:58,541 --> 00:37:00,833
really think of you as my son.

634
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:03,375
[sighs]

635
00:37:03,458 --> 00:37:04,750
Thank you, sir.

636
00:37:13,208 --> 00:37:14,291
[music fades]

637
00:37:16,208 --> 00:37:18,208
[snoring]

638
00:37:28,291 --> 00:37:29,125
[door opening]

639
00:37:29,208 --> 00:37:30,666
[Karasuma] Please, come in.

640
00:37:30,750 --> 00:37:32,625
Mr. Kujo, you have a visitor.

641
00:37:33,541 --> 00:37:34,541
Please.

642
00:37:37,625 --> 00:37:38,625
Sir.

643
00:37:39,166 --> 00:37:41,333
Sir! You have a visitor.

644
00:37:41,958 --> 00:37:42,833
[groans]

645
00:37:42,916 --> 00:37:44,458
Come in. I'm Kujo.

646
00:37:44,541 --> 00:37:46,208
Oh, you… you reek of alcohol.

647
00:37:46,291 --> 00:37:47,875
Does he know what he's doing?

648
00:37:48,500 --> 00:37:50,291
How about you handle my case instead?

649
00:37:50,375 --> 00:37:51,250
Yeah, no.

650
00:37:52,375 --> 00:37:53,541
Please, have a seat.

651
00:38:00,916 --> 00:38:02,083
So, your name?

652
00:38:03,583 --> 00:38:04,625
It's Iemori.

653
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:07,500
And my first name's Hanae.

654
00:38:07,583 --> 00:38:08,875
Ms. Iemori.

655
00:38:10,750 --> 00:38:12,458
How can we be of help to you?

656
00:38:13,583 --> 00:38:15,666
I think that
my father's estate was stolen.

657
00:38:15,750 --> 00:38:18,083
- [Kujo] His estate?
- [tense music playing]

658
00:38:18,166 --> 00:38:22,541
We found a handwritten will that said
he wanted to leave his entire estate

659
00:38:22,625 --> 00:38:24,375
to an incorporated association.

660
00:38:24,458 --> 00:38:26,666
He would never have done
something like that.

661
00:38:27,708 --> 00:38:31,000
Before he passed, tell me,
were you and your father living together?

662
00:38:31,083 --> 00:38:32,125
We weren't.

663
00:38:32,208 --> 00:38:35,916
He had dementia,
so was… living in a facility.

664
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:37,500
Dementia?

665
00:38:39,125 --> 00:38:41,583
They took… advantage of that.

666
00:38:42,791 --> 00:38:44,541
And got him to write this.

667
00:38:46,083 --> 00:38:47,583
By "they," you mean who?

668
00:38:48,083 --> 00:38:50,750
[Ms. Iemori] The head of the nursing home
and his lawyer.

669
00:38:53,250 --> 00:38:57,166
<i>My father, Shigenori Iemori,</i>
<i>wrote that he would give all of his assets</i>

670
00:38:57,250 --> 00:38:59,583
<i>to an incorporated association</i>
<i>called Kikogi.</i>

671
00:38:59,666 --> 00:39:02,708
<i>A man named Sugawara,</i>
<i>who runs the nursing home,</i>

672
00:39:02,791 --> 00:39:06,791
<i>and his lawyer,</i>
<i>Yuzo Yamashiro, forced him to write it.</i>

673
00:39:08,083 --> 00:39:10,958
Please, sir, I am begging you.

674
00:39:11,541 --> 00:39:16,125
I need the estate back from Sugawara
and that sleazy crooked lawyer of his.

675
00:39:20,416 --> 00:39:21,958
I'm sorry, but I…

676
00:39:23,291 --> 00:39:25,125
I'm afraid I can't take your case.
I'm sorry.

677
00:39:25,791 --> 00:39:27,000
Why though?

678
00:39:28,166 --> 00:39:31,500
I've been looking for days,
passed around from lawyer to lawyer.

679
00:39:32,500 --> 00:39:36,416
Mibu said that Mr. Kujo
would never turn down a case

680
00:39:36,500 --> 00:39:38,666
no matter what the odds of winning are.

681
00:39:40,958 --> 00:39:42,208
But this time, it's impossible.

682
00:39:42,291 --> 00:39:43,458
Listen!

683
00:39:44,375 --> 00:39:46,375
Another lawyer's defrauding
helpless seniors,

684
00:39:46,458 --> 00:39:48,083
and you refuse to do anything about it?

685
00:39:51,208 --> 00:39:52,500
[music fades]

686
00:39:53,958 --> 00:39:56,125
[closing theme song playing]

687
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:33,916
[music fades]
